{
  "texts": [
    "The origin of possibility semantics for propositional modal logic is Humberstone 1981.",
    "The important differences between Humberstone's frames and our possibility frames are discussed in § 2.3 and Appendix § B.1.",
    "There is also a more superficial difference, namely that Humberstone's [1981] valuations were partial functions V: Φ × S → {0, 1} satisfying the condition of stability and resolution from above, but which Humberstone called 'persistence' and 'refinability'.",
    "Since the different approaches to valuations in the literature may be confusing, we provide the following guide.",
    "Remark 8.3 (Three Approaches to Valuations in Possibility Semantics).There are three approaches to valuation functions in the literature on possibility semantics:1."
  ]
}